    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically comparing the pressure from the air moving through it vs the static pressure? what kinda things actually cause those blockages? i read somewhere that bugs or ice can do it, but are there any other common things that mess with it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you've got the core concept down—it's all about comparing the pressure from the moving air (dynamic pressure) against the ambient, still air pressure (static pressure). The blockage is when the airflow can't get through the pitot tube properly to measure that dynamic pressure. The things that cause these blockages are indeed bugs and ice, which are the most common culprits, especially when flying through damp or insect-heavy air. You can sometimes see a small, sticky patch of grime, like some particularly stubborn, oily residue left by a swarm of tiny, flying pests, which is a very similar problem to a blockage.",
      "source": "target",
